'''Abraham''' (died 1080) was [[Bishop of St David's|Bishop]] of [[St Davids|St David's and the Cathedral Close]] in [[Pembrokeshire]], Wales from 1078, when he succeeded [[Sulien]], until his murder in 1080, during a Viking invasion.<ref name="DWB" /><ref name="Evans">{{cite book|author1=J. Wyn Evans|author2=Jonathan M. Wooding|title=St David of Wales: Cult, Church and Nation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LN9DSKZfItcC&pg=PA33|year=2007|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-84383-322-2|pages=33, 84, 300}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Paul Dalton|author2=Charles Insley|author3=Louise J. Wilkinson|title=Cathedrals, Communities and Conflict in the Anglo-Norman World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FFgt22pS8igC&pg=PA99|year=2011|publisher=Boydell Press|isbn=978-1-84383-620-9|pages=99, 110}}</ref>{{efn|St David's Cathedral states that Abraham was bishop from 1076 to 1078.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stdavidscathedral.org.uk/index.php?id=721|title=Past & Present Bishops & Deans|website=St David's Cathedral|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="AC">{{cite book|title=Archaeologia Cambrensis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OE1AAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA78|year=1892|publisher=W. Pickering|page=78}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Philip Appleby Robson|title=The Cathedral Church of Saint David's: a short history and description of the fabric and episcopal buildings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qhRNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA79|year=1901|publisher=G. Bell|pages=79, 93}}</ref> His year of death as given by the cathedral as 1078<ref name="AC" /> and 1080.<ref name="Gatehouse">{{cite web|url=http://www.stdavidscathedral.org.uk/index.php?id=723|title=Tower Gate House and Bell Tower|website=St David's Cathedral|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stdavidscathedral.org.uk/index.php?id=678|title=A Brief History Of The Cathedral|website=St David's Cathedral|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>}} Sulien then served again as bishop.<ref name="Evans" />

His two sons, Isaac and Hedd, are commemorated on a ''c.'' early-twelfth-century stone cross discovered in 1891 in St David's Cathedral. The Abraham Stone now resides in the Tower Gate House and Bell Tower of the original cathedral city.<ref name="Gatehouse" /><ref name="DWB">{{cite web|title=Abraham (Bishop of St David's)|url=http://yba.llgc.org.uk/en/s-ABRA-HAM-1080.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|accessdate=8 December 2015}}</ref>

