[[File:Shigandang.JPG|thumb|A [[Mount Tai]] Shigandang(泰山石敢當) in [[Beijing]], China.]] [[File:OkinawaIshiganto.jpg|thumb|A Shigandang in [[Okinawa]], Japan]] '''Shigandang''' ({{zh|t=石敢當|w=shih-kan-tang|p=shí gǎn dāng}}; Japanese: {{lang|ja|石敢當}} ''ishigantō'') is an ornamental [[stone tablet]] with writings,<ref>[http://www.fushantang.com/1003/c1011.html 石敢當][http://www.masterlung.com/course06.html 泰山石敢當][http://www.sinchew.com.my/node/67322 泰山石敢當]</ref> which is used to exorcise evil spirits in [[east Asia]]. The Shigandang are often associated with [[Mount Tai]] and are often placed on street intersections or three-way junctions, especially in the crossing, which is often considered a fierce place (凶位). Many Shigandang have been replaced by stone written with [[Nianfo|Nāmó Ēmítuófó]].
