{{distinguish|Steve Jackson (British game designer)}} {{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}
{{Infobox person | image = Steve jackson at lucca games 2006.jpg <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people. See [[WP:NONFREE]]. --> | image_size = 200px | | name = Steve Jackson | caption = Steve Jackson signing autographs at [[Lucca Comics and Games|Lucca Comics & Games]] 2006 gaming convention in [[Lucca]], Italy. | birth_date = c. {{birth year and age|1953}}{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | education = | occupation = [[Game designer]], founder of [[Steve Jackson Games]] | spouse = | parents = | children = | known_for = [[Car Wars]], [[GURPS]], [[Munchkin (card game)|Munchkin]] }}
'''Steve Jackson''' (born c. 1953{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}) is an American [[game designer]]. He designed the role-playing game ''[[GURPS]]'' and the card game ''[[Munchkin (card game)|Munchkin]]''.
==Education== Steve Jackson is a 1974 [[alumnus|graduate]] of [[Rice University]],<ref>[https://scholarship.rice.edu/handle/1911/61711 "Rice University Class of 1974 Commencement program"]</ref> where he was a resident of [[Baker College (Rice University)|Baker College]] before moving to [[Sid Richardson College]] when it opened in 1971.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} Jackson briefly attended the [[University of Texas School of Law|UT Law School]], but left to pursue a career in game design.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|102}}
==Career== ===1970s: Metagaming Concepts=== While working at [[Metagaming Concepts]], Jackson developed ''[[Monsters! Monsters!]]'' (''ca''1976) based on a design by [[Ken St. Andre]] related to his ''[[Tunnels & Trolls]]'' role-playing game, and ''[[Godsfire]]'' (1976), a 3D space conquest game designed by [[Lynn Willis]].<ref name="designers">{{Cite book|author=Shannon Appelcline|title=Designers & Dragons|publisher=Mongoose Publishing|year=2011| isbn= 978-1-907702-58-7}}</ref>{{rp|78}} Jackson's first design for the company was ''[[Ogre (game)|Ogre]]'' (1977), followed by ''[[G.E.V. (board game)|G.E.V.]]'' (1978), which were set in the same futuristic universe that Jackson created.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|79}}
Jackson became interested in ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]'', but found the various-sized dice irritating and the combat rules confusing and unsatisfying, and did not like the lack of tactics, so he designed ''[[Melee (game)|Melee]]'' in response.<ref name="designers" />{{rp|79}} Jackson joined the [[Society for Creative Anachronism|SCA]] to gain a better understanding of combat, but he soon became more interested and started fighting in SCA live-action combat as Vargskol, the Viking-Celt.<ref name="designers" />{{rp|79}} Metagaming also published his game ''[[Wizard (board game)|Wizard]]''.<ref name="HG">{{Cite book | contribution=[[Paranoia (role-playing game)|Paranoia]] | title=Hobby Games: The 100 Best | last=Jackson | first=Steve | authorlink= | editor-last=Lowder | editor-first=James | editor-link=James Lowder | publisher=[[Green Ronin Publishing]] | year=2007 | pages=231–235 | isbn=978-1-932442-96-0}}</ref>
While designing ''Melee'', Jackson realized this idea could be expanded into a full fantasy role-playing game to compete with ''D&D'', and started working on ''[[The Fantasy Trip]]''. While the game was originally scheduled for release in February 1978, the design and development required more work than Jackson had anticipated and the game was not released until March 1980.<ref name="designers" />{{rp|79}} [[Howard Thompson (game designer)|Howard Thompson]], owner of Metagaming, decided to release ''The Fantasy Trip'' as four separate books instead of a boxed set, and changed his production methods so that Jackson would not be able to check the final proofs of the game. As a result of these actions, Jackson left Metagaming and founded [[Steve Jackson Games]] later that year.<ref name="designers" />{{rp|79–80}}
===1980s-: Steve Jackson Games=== His game ''[[Raid on Iran]]'' was an immediate success.<ref name="HG"/> Jackson bought ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' from Metagaming, and sold the rights to ''The Fantasy Trip'' to Metagaming. However, Thompson sought legal action against SJG for the rights to a short wargame called ''One-Page Bulge'', and the lawsuit was settled with an agreement that was reached on November 26, 1981 which gave Jackson full rights to ''One-Page Bulge'', and to ''Ogre'' and ''G.E.V.'' (whose ownership was questioned during the legal proceedings).<ref name="designers" />{{rp|80}} Jackson tried to purchase ''The Fantasy Trip'' from Thompson after Metagaming ceased operations in April 1983, but Thompson declined the offered price of $250,000.<ref name="designers" />{{rp|81}}
Jackson designed or co-designed many of the games published by SJ Games, including minigames such as ''[[Car Wars]]'' (1981) and ''[[Illuminati (game)|Illuminati]]'' (1983), ''[[Undead (board game)|Undead]]'' (1981), and a published version of an informal game played on college campuses, called ''[[Killer: The Game of Assassination|Killer]]''.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|103}} Jackson wanted to get into computer gaming software in the early 1980s, but instead wound up licensing gaming rights to [[Origin Systems]], which produced games such as ''[[Autoduel]]'' (1985) and ''[[Ogre (video game)|Ogre]]'' (1986).<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|104}}
Jackson became interested in designing and publishing a new roleplaying system in the middle of 1981, intending it to be detailed and realistic, logical and well-organized, and adaptable to any setting and any level of play; he announced ''[[GURPS]]'' in 1983, although the company's magazines delayed development of ''GURPS'' until 1984, making the combat system book ''[[Man to Man: Fantasy Combat from GURPS]]'' (1985) available for Origins 1985, and the full ''GURPS Basic Set'' appeared the next year in 1986.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|105}} In 1995, [[Sean Punch]] took over for Jackson as the ''GURPS'' line editor.<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|110}}
===Recent years=== Jackson also designed the strategy card games ''[[Munchkin (card game)|Munchkin]]'' (2001)<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|112}} and [[Ninja Burger]] (2003), and the dice games [[Zombie Dice]] (2010) and [[Cthulhu Dice]] (2010), as well as Zombie Dice variants [[Trophy Buck]] (2011) and [[Dino Hunt Dice]] (2013).
Jackson has exhibited his elaborate [[Chaos Machine]] at several science fiction or [[wargaming]] conventions, including the 2006 [[Worldcon]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.wired.com/worldcon/2007/01/chaos_machine.html |title=WorldCon 2006 |accessdate=2007-02-26 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214015243/http://blog.wired.com/worldcon/2007/01/chaos_machine.html |archivedate=December 14, 2007 |df=mdy-all }} from ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]''</ref>
On May 11, 2012, Steve Jackson's [[Kickstarter]] funding project for the 6th Edition of his ''Ogre'' game became the highest grossing boardgame project at Kickstarter, with 5,512 backers pledging a total of $923,680. The success of the ''Ogre Designer's Edition'' project has prompted a new project (date of start/finish unknown at this time) to help re-launch the popular ''Car Wars'' franchise as well. The use of Kickstarter as a combination of market research tool and funding program for development is a first in the gaming industry.<ref>[[Kickstarter]] project page for [http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/847271320/ogre-designers-edition ''Ogre Designer's Edition'']</ref>
===The two "Steve Jacksons"=== Jackson is often mistaken for [[Steve Jackson (UK game designer)|Steve Jackson]], a British [[gamebook]] and video game writer who co-founded [[Games Workshop]]. The confusion is exacerbated by the fact that while the UK Jackson was co-creator of the ''[[Fighting Fantasy]]'' gamebook series, the US Jackson also wrote three books in this series (''[[Scorpion Swamp]]'', ''[[Demons of the Deep]]'', and ''[[Robot Commando]]''), and the books did not acknowledge that this was a different 'Steve Jackson'.<ref>[http://sj.sjgames.com/sjbio.html Steve Jackson – Biography and Public Warning] from Steve Jackson's personal website</ref>
== 1990 Secret Service incident and legal actions == {{Main|Steve Jackson Games, Inc. v. United States Secret Service}} On March 1, 1990, the [[United States Secret Service]] raided the offices of Steve Jackson Games based on suspicion of illegal hacker activity by game designer [[Loyd Blankenship]], and seized (among other materials and media) his manuscript for ''[[GURPS Cyberpunk]]''; when Jackson went to Secret Service headquarters the next day to retrieve his book drafts, he was told that ''GURPS Cyberpunk'' was a "handbook for computer crime", despite his protestations that it was just a game. SJG filed a successful lawsuit against the government, which went to trial in 1993 as ''[[Steve Jackson Games, Inc. v. United States Secret Service]]'', which was made possible through the newly created civil-rights organization [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]].<ref name="designers"/>{{rp|108–109}}
== Personal interests ==
Jackson is an avid collector of [[Lego Pirates|pirate]]-themed [[Lego]] sets. He has written a miniatures game that uses Pirate sets, ''Evil Stevie's Pirate Game'', and has run it at several conventions.
Jackson has combined his fondness for model trains and [[LEGO]] through the [[LEGO]] train community and has been an active member of several [[LEGO Users Groups]] including TBRR (Texas Brick Railroad) and the Texas LEGO Users Group.
==Honors== *Jackson has received over a dozen [[Origins Awards]]. *In 1982, he became the youngest game designer to be inducted in the [[Charles Roberts Awards Hall of Fame|Origins Awards Hall of Fame]]. *His role-playing game ''[[GURPS]]'' and card game ''[[Munchkin (card game)|Munchkin]]'' were named to the Origins Hall of Fame for 1999 and 2012 respectively.<ref name="Origins">{{cite web | url = http://www.originsawards.net/hall-of-fame/ | title = AAGAD Hall of Fame | publisher = Academy of Adventure Gaming Arts & Design (AAGAD) | accessdate = December 20, 2017| df = mdy-all }}</ref><ref name="sjg_awards">{{cite web | url=http://www.sjgames.com/general/awards.html | title=Awards for Steve Jackson Games | publisher=Steve Jackson Games | accessdate = February 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name="buffalo_deck">{{cite web| url=http://www.flyingbuffalo.com/pokerdeck.htm| title=Poker Deck| publisher=Flying Buffalo| accessdate=February 11, 2014}}</ref>
He was honored as a "famous game designer" by being featured as the king of clubs in [[Flying Buffalo]]'s 2011 Famous Game Designers Playing Card Deck.<ref name="buffalo_deck" />
