__NOTOC__ {{infobox book | name = The Einstein Intersection | title_orig = | translator = | image = Image:Delany Einstein-Intersection.jpg | caption = First edition (paperback) | author = [[Samuel R. Delany]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = [[Jack Gaughan]] | country = United States | language = English | series = | genre = [[Science fiction]] novel | publisher = [[Ace Books]] | release_date = 1967 | english_release_date = | media_type = Print (hardback & paperback) | pages = 142 pp | isbn = <!-- First edition published prior to adoption of ISBN standard --> | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Einstein Intersection''''' is a 1967 [[science fiction]] novel by [[Samuel R. Delany]]. It won the [[Nebula Award]] for [[Nebula Award for Best Novel|Best Novel]] in 1967<ref name="WWE-1967">{{cite web| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1967 | title = 1967 Award Winners & Nominees| work = Worlds Without End| accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> and was nominated for the [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Novel|Best Novel]] in 1968.<ref name="WWE-1968">{{cite web| url = http://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1968 | title = 1968 Award Winners & Nominees| work = Worlds Without End| accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> Delany's intended title for the book was ''A Fabulous, Formless Darkness''.
The novel is purportedly influenced by [[Marcel Camus]]' 1959 film ''[[Black Orpheus]]''. The protagonist, Lo Lobey, is loosely based on the character of Orpheus, and the character of Kid Death is likewise based on Death in that film.
==Reception== [[Algis Budrys]], after noting that Delany "has about as little discipline as any writer who has tried his hand" at science fiction and that ''The Einstein Intersection'' was a book "whose structure and purpose on its own terms are not realized", declared that the author "simply operates on a plane which [[Robert Heinlein]] never dreamed of, nor [[John W. Campbell]], nor – take a deep breath – [[Theodore Sturgeon|Ted Sturgeon]], [[Ray Bradbury]], nor anyone else we could have put forward as being a poet" before 1960 and "urgently recommended" the novel".<ref name="budrys196710">{{Cite magazine |last=Budrys |first=Algis |author= |last2= |first2= |date=October 1967 |title=Galaxy Bookshelf |department= |url=https://archive.org/stream/Galaxy_v26n01_1967-10_modified#page/n175/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=188-194 |type= }}</ref> In February 1968 he named the book the best novel of the year.<ref name="budrys196802">{{Cite magazine |last=Budrys |first=Algis |author= |last2= |first2= |date=February 1968 |title=Galaxy Bookshelf |department= |url=https://archive.org/stream/Galaxy_v26n03_1968-02_modified#page/n99/mode/2up |magazine=Galaxy Science Fiction |pages=157-162 |type= }}</ref>
